Just jotting down our offline discussion about this. So the main concern is that this is pretty specific and even we wanted to roll out something more general it may be weird to have both.

So the idea would be we expose a `params.json` underneath the `.chalice` directory where you can provide parameters to use in your `config.json`. So a sample `params.json` would look like:

```json
{
  "table_name": "MyTable"
}
````
Then for each stage you can vary these parameters by specifying the name `{stage-name}-params.json`. So if a config file looked like this:
```json
{
  "stages": {
    "dev": {
      "api_gateway_stage": "api",
      "environment_variables": {
          "TABLE_NAME": "{table_name}"
       }
    }
  },
  "version": "2.0",
  "app_name": "helloworld"
}
```
From there when a `chalice deploy` happens, it will replace the value with the value from `params.json` to do the deployment. Then when a `chalice package` happens, we would just create parameters and make reference to the parameters.

The main reasons that this approach is nice is:

1) It is general. The parameter replacement can be used for any config variable.
2) It still allows you to do a single `chalice package` command and then just do deployments using the `params.json` to change the parameter values when deploying.
3) It solves the issue when you commit the `config.json` to the repository and each dev committing to the repository have different values in their `config.json` and you end up clobbering changes. The `params.json` would be like the `deployed.json` where it would not be committed and thus the local values would not be clobbered.

