Hi @ozancaglayan , sorry for the delay in replying.
While I agree that it is very useful to have a functionality to extract intermediate layers from a network, I'm less sure about the current approach, as it is specific to sequential modules, and requires specific knowledge of the network architecture.

One alternative proposal would be to have hooks returning the results for you. For example
```python
class GetLayer(torch.nn.Module):
 def __init__(self, model, layers):
   super(GetLayer, self).__init__()
   self.model = model
   self.layers = layers

   self.outputs = OrderedDict()
   def _create_hook(name):
     def hook(module, input, output):
       self.outputs[name] = output.clone()
     return hook

   self.handles = {}
   for name, module in model.named_modules():
     if name in layers:
       self.handles[name] = module.register_forward_hook(_create_hook(name))

 def forward(self, *args, **kwargs):
   output = self.model(*args, **kwargs)
   return self.outputs
```

This approach enables you to extract layers for arbitrary models (such as resnets, etc).
One drawback of it is that you need to perform a full forward of the model, so it can be less efficient. Also, it attaches hooks to the model, so you need to properly clean them up afterwards or else your original model will still have the hooks attached. Also, the serialized name of the model would change (because of the extra `nn.Module` that is added).
For those reasons, I'm not 100% satisfied either with such an approach, but I'm not sure yet how we can do better.
Do you have any ideas?

This is already possible, and is used extensively on [Mimic](https://github.com/rackerlabs/mimic/).

I thought that we even had an example of doing this in the documentation, but apparently you have to sort of infer it from cobbling together a combination of ["return anything"](http://klein.readthedocs.io/en/latest/introduction/1-gettingstarted.html#return-anything), ["static files"](http://klein.readthedocs.io/en/latest/introduction/1-gettingstarted.html?highlight=branch#static-files) and ["non-global state"](http://klein.readthedocs.io/en/latest/examples/nonglobalstate.html).

The way that you do it is using *branch routes*, and *bound apps*, like so:

```python

from klein import route, run, Klein

class UsersApp(object):
    routes = Klein()
    @routes.route("/<string:username>")
    def an_user(self, request, username):
        request.setHeader('content-type', 'text/plain')
        return 'A User Named "{username}".'.format(username=username)

class MathApp(object):
    mathroutes = Klein()
    @mathroutes.route("/add/<int:a>/<int:b>")
    def add(self, request, a, b):
        return str(a + b)


@route("/users", branch=True)
def users_app(request):
    return UsersApp().routes.resource()

@route("/math", branch=True)
def math_app(request):
    return MathApp().mathroutes.resource()

@route("/")
def hi(request):
    return "Hi"

run("localhost", 8123)
```

Here we have two apps - "math" and "users", each of which is "mounted" into the URL hierarchy by the top-level branch route.  So you can go to `/users/janet` or you can go to `/math/add/3/4`.

This ticket is asking for an implementation, which I don't think we need, so I'm going to close it.  I do think there's a valid issue here though, which is for there to be some clear documentation of this pattern, but I'm not sure how to articulate it in terms of a useful example, so I'm not opening that right away.  I would definitely appreciate it if someone else could open it though!

