We already kind of have both `List` and `ProxyList` but they're mixed together in `GangaList.py`. This would split them so that `List` is in `Objects.py` and `ProxyList` is in `Proxy.py`.

As you say, `ProxyList` is very small and is simply applying the proxy wrapping to the methods it exposes. My implementation uses a metaclass to wrap these methods so that `ProxyClass` is simply (subject to change):
```python
class ProxyList(GPIProxyObject, collections.MutableSequence):
    """This is an object which lives in the proxy layer to provide proxy wrapping to all its elements"""
    __metaclass__ = ProxyListMetaClass

    @ProxyListMetaClass.proxy_wrap
    def __init__(self, _list=None):
        if _list is None:
            _list = []

        # Set up the standard proxy interface
        self._impl = List(copy.deepcopy(_list))
        self._impl._proxyObject = self

exportToGPI('ProxyList', ProxyList, 'Classes')
```

Likewise, `List` is very simple and is just (likewise subject to change):
```python
class List(list, Node):
    """This is as close to a Python list as possible. The only thing it adds is the correct management of parents."""
    _parent = None

    def _setParent(self, parent):
        self._parent = parent
        for element in self:
            if isinstance(element, Node):
                element._setParent(parent)
        self._dirty = False

    def __setitem__(self, index, value):
        if isinstance(value, Node):
            value._setParent(self._parent)
        return super(List, self).__setitem__(index, value)  # Call the base method

    def insert(self, index, value):
        if isinstance(value, Node):
            value._setParent(self._parent)
        return super(List, self).insert(index, value)  # Call the base method
```

`SubJobXMLList` was mentioned as a potential future, not as an immediate change. As I said, it would be based on `List`, not on `ProxyList` so it wouldn't have any proxy code in at all. It would however perhaps make the parent tracking much easier.

As for the naming of `List` vs. `GangaList`: if we made any of the changes I mentioned above I would very likely rename my `List` to `GangaList` to reduce the renamings needed (although having different names would allow both to exist for a while).

`List` will be serialisable by it overriding `accept`. It will map exactly to the `<sequence>` in XML (none of this code is written yet).

In spirit you can see my proposed changes as little more than simply splitting out `GangaList.py` into two classes so that their individual purposes are more clearly defined. This will simplify the code and reduce the bugs that we have been seeing creeping in recently with parenting etc.

@jwhui 2 questions:

1) It seems that Border Router API has 2 methods which will be 100% identical in my Server API, namely `otBorderRouterGetNetData()` and `otBorderRouterRegister()`. They just seem to operate on the underlying Network Data Local structure directly. I would strongly recommend getting some public API to do that, instead of duplicating the code between Border Router and Server implementations. I.e. having 2 identical methods like this:

```
otError otBorderRouterGetNetData(otInstance *aInstance, bool aStable, uint8_t *aData, uint8_t *aDataLength)
{
    otError error = OT_ERROR_NONE;

    VerifyOrExit(aData != NULL && aDataLength != NULL, error = OT_ERROR_INVALID_ARGS);

    aInstance->mThreadNetif.GetNetworkDataLocal().GetNetworkData(aStable, aData, *aDataLength);

exit:
    return error;
}
```
doesn't seem a good idea. I would even go a step further and mark `otBorderRouterGetNetData` as deprecated in favour of `otNetworkDataLocalGetData`, same for `otBorderRouterRegister()` to be replaced by `otNetworkDataLocalRegister`.

What do you think?

2) The implementation of `otBorderRouterGetNetData` seem to have subtle bug - it doesn't check the length of passed buffer. I.e. if caller will have too short buffer, `otBorderRouterGetNetData` will not check the length and call `aInstance->mThreadNetif.GetNetworkDataLocal().GetNetworkData()`, which in turn will not check the length neither, and happily proceed with `memcpy` - leading to memory corruption. Was that a bug or intentional optimization? If so, then https://github.com/Nopik/openthread/blob/master/include/openthread/border_router.h#L60-L61 is heavily misleading and should be changed to `out` and something like "You need to provide at least 256 bytes." or something like that.

